<DOC><DOCNO> AP891219-0139 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-89 2110EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     12-19 0271</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Haiti,0282</SECOND><HEAD>Haitian Cabinet Reshuffle, Change In Army High Command</HEAD><BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><TEXT>   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A new Cabinet was sworn in Tuesdayafter Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril replaced seven ministers, the policechief and a top army officer in the biggest government shakeupsince he took power last year.   Franck Paultre, the former public works minister, replacedLeonce Thelusma as finance minister in the reshuffle, announced onstate-run TV late Monday.   Thelusma was criticized for his foreign currency-control policyand for having signed a controversial agreement with theInternational Monetary Fund.   Brig. Gen. Fritz Romulus, the former airport chief who was newlypromoted from colonel, replaced Brig. Gen. Acedius Saint-Louis asdefense and interior minister.   Saint-Louis drew fire as being ineffective in fighting urbangangsterism. Romulus, reputed to be a moderate, is the onlymilitary man in the 13-member Cabinet.   Serge Petit-Frere replaced Remy Zamor as education minister.   Teachers accused Zamor of authoritarianism. They struck severaltimes, protesting they had not been paid. They overwhelminglyrejected an insurance plan Zamor presented for teachers and it wasshelved.   Also replaced were the ministers of commerce, planning,agriculture and public administration.   Col. Henri Robert Augustin, the police chief, was replaced byLt. Col. Martial Romulus, who was military attache at the HaitianEmbassy in Washington.   Maj. Gen. Max Valles, one of Haiti's nine generals, was retired.For six weeks in 1986, Valles was a member of the provisional juntawhich took over after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled intoFrench exile.   Avril came to power in a bloodless coup in September 1988 thatousted Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy.</TEXT></DOC>